      "\nLet's think about how to approach this. When working with product types in Lean, we often use the `ext` tactic to prove equality of functions. For product types, we need to prove equality of both components.\n\n```tactics\nimport Aesop\n\nset_option aesop.check.all true\n\n@[ext]\nstructure MyProd (α β : Type _) where\n  fst : α\n  snd : β\n\nvariable {α β γ δ ι: Type}\n\n/--\ninfo: Try this:\n\n  [apply]     ext : 1\n    · sorry\n    · sorry\n---\nwarning: declaration uses 'sorry'\n-/\n#guard_msgs in\nexample {p q : MyProd α β} : p = q := by\n  aesop? (add safe Aesop.BuiltinRules.ext)\n    (config := { warnOnNonterminal := false })\n  all_goals sorry\n\n/--\ninfo: Try this:\n\n  [apply]     ext : 1\n    · sorry\n    · ext : 1\n      · sorry\n      · sorry\n---\nwarning: declaration uses 'sorry'\n-/\n#guard_msgs in\nexample {p q : MyProd α (MyProd β γ)} : p = q := by\n  aesop? (add safe Aesop.BuiltinRules.ext)\n    (config := { warnOnNonterminal := false })\n  all_goals sorry\n\n/--\ninfo: Try this:\n\n  [apply]     ext : 1\n    · ext x : 1\n      sorry\n    · sorry\n---\nwarning: declaration uses 'sorry'\n-/\n#guard_msgs in\nexample {p q : MyProd (α → β) γ} : p = q := by\n  aesop? (add safe Aesop.BuiltinRules.ext)\n    (config := { warnOnNonterminal := false })\n  all_goals sorry\n```\n\nThe third example is the one we need to solve. Let's think about how to prove that `p = q` where `p, q : MyProd (α → β) γ`.\n\nWhen we have `p = q`, we need to show that `p.fst = q.fst` and `p.snd = q.snd`.\n\n- `p.fst` is of type `α → β`\n- `p.snd` is of type `γ`\n\nSimilarly for `q`.\n\nSo, to prove `p = q`, we need to:\n1. Prove `p.fst = q.fst` (which are functions)\n2. Prove `p.snd = q.snd` (which are of type `γ`)\n\nFor the functions `p.fst` and `q.fst`, to prove they are equal, we need to show they have the same value at all points `x : α`. So, for any `x : α`, we need `p.fst x = q.fst x`.\n\nTherefore, the overall proof strategy should be:\n1. Use `ext` to split the goal `p = q` into two goals:\n    1. `p.fst = q.fst`\n    2. `p.snd = q.snd`\n2. For the first goal `p.fst = q.fst`:\n    a. Use `funext x` (function extensionality) to introduce an arbitrary `x : α` and change the goal to `p.fst x = q.fst x`\n    b. Use `simp` or other tactics to show that `p.fst x = q.fst x` (which will likely involve using the definitions of `p` and `q` and then simplifying)\n3. For the second goal `p.snd = q.snd`:\n    a. Use `simp` or other tactics to show that `p.snd = q.snd` (similar to the first part)\n\nSo, let's apply this to the third example:\n\n```tactics\nimport Aesop\n\nset_option aesop.check.all true\n\n@[ext]\nstructure MyProd (α β : Type _) where\n  fst : α\n  snd : β\n\nvariable {α β γ δ ι: Type}\n\n/--\ninfo: Try this:\n\n  [apply]     ext : 1\n    · sorry\n    · sorry\n---\nwarning: declaration uses 'sorry'\n-/\n#guard_msgs in\nexample {p q : MyProd α β} : p = q := by\n  aesop? (add safe Aesop.BuiltinRules.ext)\n    (config := { warnOnNonterminal := false })\n  all_goals sorry\n\n/--\ninfo: Try this:\n\n  [apply]     ext : 1\n    · sorry\n    · ext : 1\n      · sorry\n      · sorry\n---\nwarning: declaration uses 'sorry'\n-/\n#guard_msgs in\nexample {p q : MyProd α (MyProd β γ)} : p = q := by\n  aesop? (add safe Aesop.BuiltinRules.ext)\n    (config := { warnOnNonterminal := false })\n  all_goals sorry\n\n/--\ninfo: Try this:\n\n  [apply]     ext : 1\n    · ext x : 1\n      sorry\n    · sorry\n---\nwarning: declaration uses 'sorry'\n-/\n#guard_msgs in\nexample {p q : MyProd (α → β) γ} : p = q := by\n```\n\nNow, we need to prove `p = q` where `p, q : MyProd (α → β) γ`.\n\n```tactics\n  ext\n  · -- Show that the first components are equal\n    funext x\n```\n\nNow, we need to prove that `p.fst x = q.fst x`. Let's look at what `p` and `q` are.\n\n`p` is `MyProd (α → β) γ`, so `p.fst` is of type `α → β` and `p.snd` is of type `γ`.\n\nSimilarly, `q` is `MyProd (α → β) γ`, so `q.fst` is of type `α → β` and `q.snd` is of type `γ`.\n\nT